was a stigmatized emblem of the lasting effects of feudalism. Today, it marks the reemergence of cultured gentlemen as an idealized model of manhood. Marc L. Moskowitz explores the fascinating history of the game, as well as providing a vivid snapshot of Chinese Go players today. Go Nation uses this game to come to a better understanding of Chinese masculinity, nationalism, and class, as the PRC reconfigures its history and traditions to meet the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGamesxSocial aspectszChina. 0aGo (Game)zChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aasia scholars.  aasian studies.  aboard games.  achina.  achinese culture.  achinese games.  achinese nationalism.  achinese traditions.  aclass differences.  acompetitive culture.  acultural revolution.  aculture and politics.  aeast asia.  afeudalism.  afour noble arts.  agame historians.  agame history.  agames and sports.  agentlemen.  ago players.  ago.  aimperial times.  alogic games.  amanhood.  amasculinity.  apopular games.  arecreation and games.  areligious enlightenment.  atraditional games.  aweiqi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027631440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095693340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956933/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  a